  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The warning against unkindness towards an enemy is followed by still further prohibitions of injustice in questions of right: viz., in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 23:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a warning against perverting the right of the poor in his cause; in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 23:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a general command to keep far away from a false matter, and not to slay the innocent and righteous, i.e., not to be guilty of judicial murder, together with the threat that God would not justify the sinner; and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the command not to accept presents, i.e., to be bribed by gifts, because \"the gift makes seeing men (פּקחים open eyes) blind, and perverts the causes of the just.\" The rendering \"words of the righteous\" is not correct; for even if we are to understand the expression \"seeing men\" as referring to judges, the \"righteous\" can only refer to those who stand at the bar, and have right on their side, which judges who accept of bribes may turn into wrong.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]